{
  "query": "What are the observed outcomes of transplanting or seeding organisms onto intertidal artificial structures in Australian estuaries?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies in Australia, transplanting oysters onto intertidal artificial structures supported macroalgae, mobile and non\u2011mobile invertebrates, and fish species that were absent from surfaces without transplanted oysters (3472). Effects on combined macroalgae and invertebrate richness/diversity were mixed and depended on site and the presence/size of grooves or ledges (3472). One Australian study found increased mobile invertebrate species richness following oyster transplantation (3472). For fishes, two Australian studies reported no increase in species richness, while another found mixed effects depending on surface grooves/ridges and site (3472). Combined macroalgae and invertebrate abundance showed no increase in one Australian study and mixed effects in another, influenced by grooves/ledges (3472). Mobile invertebrate abundance responses were mixed across studies, with one study also reporting increased non\u2011mobile invertebrate and oyster recruit abundance and decreased barnacle abundance; another found increased oyster and mobile invertebrate abundance (3472). Two Australian studies found no increase in fish abundance; one reported similar fish abundance around transplanted oysters regardless of groove/ridge presence or size (3472). Survival of transplanted invertebrates, including oysters, varied by species, site, and surface features; oyster survival was higher in grooves than on ridges in one study, while survival in grooves versus ledges varied by site in another; some studies simply reported a proportion survived (3472). One Australian study found transplanting oysters and/or coralline algae did not increase the time fishes spent interacting with surfaces or the number of bites, though benthic fishes took more bites from surfaces with transplanted oysters than with algae plus oysters, regardless of grooves/ridges (3472).",
